time (about 12 years) (Forster et al. 2021). Reducing methane emissions therefore affects warming rates in the near term, resulting in benefits for ecosystems and people, and enabling humans to adapt to climate change (UNEP 2021). Estimates of the remaining global carbon budget for 1.5\u00b0C assume that methane is strongly reduced by at least 30 per cent, 40 per cent and 50 per cent relative to 2020 levels in 2030, 2040 and 2050 respectively (IPCC 2018).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2e676af3-4e67-416f-a457-48aec381ade4": {"__data__": {"id_": "2e676af3-4e67-416f-a457-48aec381ade4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.unep.org/resources/emissions-gap-report-2022", "Author": "United Nations Environment Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Environment Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Emissions Gap Report 2022", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.unep.org/resources/emissions-gap-report-2022", "Author": "United Nations Environment Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Environment Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "03c94729377ca7cf68549ff77cd4f077beae3fa747dbab15604c194be3b8039a"}, "2": {"node_id": "7a3b3549-e4cd-473d-9f38-2c97d12d68da", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.unep.org/resources/emissions-gap-report-2022", "Author": "United Nations Environment Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Environment Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "940f8b1ae49046d3af4dd95c61e944f39b8a6bef8aa2a0c09210519bcd027ee1"}}, "hash": "81cb9e875790848d86edfeabed3c8872941ac4ac5068b19257d9702363a1d843", "text": "Every ca 100 Mt shortfall in methane reductions compared with these benchmarks diminishes the already very small cumulative remaining carbon budg